&gt; &gt; to  &gt; &gt; another without understanding the problem.
&gt; &gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;  &gt; &gt; But I can infer a bit about the problem from the fact you are 
&gt; &gt; using  &gt; &gt; the concept of a person and things a person can do (eat, 
&gt; &gt; sleep,  &gt; work).
&gt; &gt;  &gt; &gt; I&#39;ll assume here that sleep() and work() change the 
&gt; state of the  
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; person (to sleeping and working respectively) . Maybe 
&gt; there is a  
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; substate when working that says what work you are doing. Let&#39;s 
